{"tool":"sql_query","args":{"query":"SELECT variant_id, drag_coefficient, frontal_area_m2, curb_mass_kg, printf('%.3f', CAST(drag_coefficient AS REAL) * CAST(frontal_area_m2 AS REAL)) AS baseline_cda_m2, printf('%.3f', (CAST(drag_coefficient AS REAL) + 0.020) * CAST(frontal_area_m2 AS REAL)) AS new_cda_m2, printf('%.3f', ((CAST(drag_coefficient AS REAL) + 0.020) * CAST(frontal_area_m2 AS REAL)) - (CAST(drag_coefficient AS REAL) * CAST(frontal_area_m2 AS REAL)) AS delta_cda_m2, printf('%.2f', 100.0 * (((CAST(drag_coefficient AS REAL) + 0.020) * CAST(frontal_area_m2 AS REAL)) - (CAST(drag_coefficient AS REAL) * CAST(frontal_area_m2 AS REAL))) / (CAST(drag_coefficient AS REAL) * CAST(frontal_area_m2 AS REAL))) AS cda_pct_change FROM vehicle_variant_configuration_specs WHERE variant_id='OAM-V0320'","limit":5}}
{"answer":"For OAM-V0320, curb_mass_kg stays unchanged at 2788 kg, so mass-dependent loads do not change. But the dossier’s aerodynamic road-load basis depends on CdA, where CdA = drag_coefficient × frontal_area_m2, so increasing drag_coefficient directly raises aerodynamic drag and therefore the power needed to maintain speed. For OAM-V0320, drag_coefficient = 0.310 and frontal_area_m2 = 2.95, giving a baseline CdA of 0.915 m2. With a +0.020 Cd increase, the new drag_coefficient would be 0.330 and the new CdA would be 0.974 m2. That is a CdA increase of 0.059 m2, or 6.45%. Because aerodynamic road load scales with CdA, the vehicle would need about 6.45% more aero-related road-load force/power at the same speed, which reduces range even though curb_mass_kg is unchanged."}
